column16047: "Brain": "A brain is an organ that serves as the center of the nervous system in all vertebrate and most invertebrate animals. It is located in the head
column16048: usually close to the sensory organs for senses such as vision. It is the most complex organ in a vertebrate's body. In a human
column16049: the cerebral cortex contains approximately 1416 billion neurons
column16050: and the estimated number of neurons in the cerebellum is 5570 billion. Each neuron is connected by synapses to several thousand other neurons. These neurons typically communicate with one another by means of long fibers called axons
column16051: which carry trains of signal pulses called action potentials to distant parts of the brain or body targeting specific recipient cells.Physiologically
column16052: brains exert centralized control over a body's other organs. They act on the rest of the body both by generating patterns of muscle activity and by driving the secretion of chemicals called hormones. This centralized control allows rapid and coordinated responses to changes in the environment. Some basic types of responsiveness such as reflexes can be mediated by the spinal cord or peripheral ganglia
column16053: but sophisticated purposeful control of behavior based on complex sensory input requires the information integrating capabilities of a centralized brain.The operations of individual brain cells are now understood in considerable detail but the way they cooperate in ensembles of millions is yet to be solved. Recent models in modern neuroscience treat the brain as a biological computer
column16054: very different in mechanism from a digital computer
column16055: but similar in the sense that it acquires information from the surrounding world
column16057: and processes it in a variety of ways.This article compares the properties of brains across the entire range of animal species
column16058: with the greatest attention to vertebrates. It deals with the human brain insofar as it shares the properties of other brains. The ways in which the human brain differs from other brains are covered in the human brain article. Several topics that might be covered here are instead covered there because much more can be said about them in a human context. The most important that are covered in the human brain article are brain disease and the effects of brain damage.AnatomyThe shape and size of the brain varies greatly between species
column16059: and identifying common features is often difficult. Nevertheless
column16060: there are a number of principles of brain architecture that apply across a wide range of species. Some aspects of brain structure are common to almost the entire range of animal species; others distinguish \"advanced\" brains from more primitive ones
column16061: or distinguish vertebrates from invertebrates.The simplest way to gain information about brain anatomy is by visual inspection
column16062: but many more sophisticated techniques have been developed. Brain tissue in its natural state is too soft to work with
column16063: but it can be hardened by immersion in alcohol or other fixatives
column16064: and then sliced apart for examination of the interior. Visually
column16065: the interior of the brain consists of areas of so-called grey matter
column16067: separated by areas of white matter
column16068: with a lighter color. Further information can be gained by staining slices of brain tissue with a variety of chemicals that bring out areas where specific types of molecules are present in high concentrations. It is also possible to examine the microstructure of brain tissue using a microscope
column16069: and to trace the pattern of connections from one brain area to another.Cellular structureThe brains of all species are composed primarily of two broad classes of cells: neurons and glial cells. Glial cells (also known as glia or neuroglia) come in several types
column16070: and perform a number of critical functions
column16076: are usually considered the most important cells in the brain.The property that makes neurons unique is their ability to send signals to specific target cells over long distances. They send these signals by means of an axon
column16077: which is a thin protoplasmic fiber that extends from the cell body and projects
column16081: sometimes in distant parts of the brain or body. The length of an axon can be extraordinary: for example
column16082: if a pyramidal cell (an excitatory neuron) of the cerebral cortex were magnified so that its cell body became the size of a human body
column16085: would become a cable a few centimeters in diameter
column16086: extending more than a kilometer. These axons transmit signals in the form of electrochemical pulses called action potentials
column16087: which last less than a thousandth of a second and travel along the axon at speeds of 1100 meters per second. Some neurons emit action potentials constantly
column16089: usually in irregular patterns; other neurons are quiet most of the time
column16090: but occasionally emit a burst of action potentials.Axons transmit signals to other neurons by means of specialized junctions called synapses. A single axon may make as many as several thousand synaptic connections with other cells. When an action potential
column16093: it causes a chemical called a neurotransmitter to be released. The neurotransmitter binds to receptor molecules in the membrane of the target cell.Synapses are the key functional elements of the brain. The essential function of the brain is cell-to-cell communication
column16094: and synapses are the points at which communication occurs. The human brain has been estimated to contain approximately 100 trillion synapses; even the brain of a fruit fly contains several million. The functions of these synapses are very diverse: some are excitatory (exciting the target cell); others are inhibitory; others work by activating second messenger systems that change the internal chemistry of their target cells in complex ways. A large number of synapses are dynamically modifiable; that is
column16095: they are capable of changing strength in a way that is controlled by the patterns of signals that pass through them. It is widely believed that activity-dependent modification of synapses is the brain's primary mechanism for learning and memory.Most of the space in the brain is taken up by axons
column16096: which are often bundled together in what are called nerve fiber tracts. A myelinated axon is wrapped in a fatty insulating sheath of myelin
column16097: which serves to greatly increase the speed of signal propagation. (There are also unmyelinated axons). Myelin is white
column16098: making parts of the brain filled exclusively with nerve fibers appear as light-colored white matter
column16099: in contrast to the darker-colored grey matter that marks areas with high densities of neuron cell bodies.EvolutionGeneric bilaterian nervous systemExcept for a few primitive organisms such as sponges (which have no nervous system) and cnidarians (which have a nervous system consisting of a diffuse nerve net)
column16100: all living multicellular animals are bilaterians
column16101: meaning animals with a bilaterally symmetric body shape (that is
column16102: left and right sides that are approximate mirror images of each other). All bilaterians are thought to have descended from a common ancestor that appeared late in the Cryogenian period
column16104: and it has been hypothesized that this common ancestor had the shape of a simple tubeworm with a segmented body. At a schematic level
column16105: that basic worm-shape continues to be reflected in the body and nervous system architecture of all modern bilaterians
column16106: including vertebrates. The fundamental bilateral body form is a tube with a hollow gut cavity running from the mouth to the anus
column16107: and a nerve cord with an enlargement (a ganglion) for each body segment
column16108: with an especially large ganglion at the front
column16109: called the brain. The brain is small and simple in some species
column16110: such as nematode worms; in other species
column16112: it is the most complex organ in the body. Some types of worms
column16114: also have an enlarged ganglion at the back end of the nerve cord
column16115: known as a \"tail brain\".There are a few types of existing bilaterians that lack a recognizable brain
column16116: including echinoderms and tunicates. It has not been definitively established whether the existence of these brainless species indicates that the earliest bilaterians lacked a brain
column16117: or whether their ancestors evolved in a way that led to the disappearance of a previously existing brain structure.InvertebratesThis category includes tardigrades
column16120: and numerous types of worms. The diversity of invertebrate body plans is matched by an equal diversity in brain structures.Two groups of invertebrates have notably complex brains: arthropods (insects
column16126: and similar molluscs). The brains of arthropods and cephalopods arise from twin parallel nerve cords that extend through the body of the animal. Arthropods have a central brain
column16128: with three divisions and large optical lobes behind each eye for visual processing. Cephalopods such as the octopus and squid have the largest brains of any invertebrates.There are several invertebrate species whose brains have been studied intensively because they have properties that make them convenient for experimental work:Fruit flies (Drosophila)
column16129: because of the large array of techniques available for studying their genetics
column16130: have been a natural subject for studying the role of genes in brain development. In spite of the large evolutionary distance between insects and mammals
column16131: many aspects of Drosophila neurogenetics have been shown to be relevant to humans. The first biological clock genes
column16133: were identified by examining Drosophila mutants that showed disrupted daily activity cycles. A search in the genomes of vertebrates revealed a set of analogous genes
column16134: which were found to play similar roles in the mouse biological clockand therefore almost certainly in the human biological clock as well. Studies done on Drosophila
column16135: also show that most neuropil regions of the brain are continuously reorganized throughout life in response to specific living conditions.The nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans
column16137: has been studied largely because of its importance in genetics. In the early 1970s
column16138: Sydney Brenner chose it as a model organism for studying the way that genes control development. One of the advantages of working with this worm is that the body plan is very stereotyped: the nervous system of the hermaphrodite contains exactly 302 neurons
column16140: making identical synaptic connections in every worm. Brenner's team sliced worms into thousands of ultrathin sections and photographed each one under an electron microscope
column16141: then visually matched fibers from section to section
column16142: to map out every neuron and synapse in the entire body. The complete neuronal wiring diagram of C.elegans  its connectome was achieved. Nothing approaching this level of detail is available for any other organism
column16143: and the information gained has enabled a multitude of studies that would otherwise have not been possible.The sea slug Aplysia californica was chosen by Nobel Prize-winning neurophysiologist Eric Kandel as a model for studying the cellular basis of learning and memory
column16144: because of the simplicity and accessibility of its nervous system
column16145: and it has been examined in hundreds of experiments.VertebratesThe first vertebrates appeared over 500 million years ago (Mya)
column16147: and may have resembled the modern hagfish in form. Jawed fish appeared by 445 Mya
column16149: reptiles by 310 Mya and mammals by 200 Mya (approximately). Each species has an equally long evolutionary history
column16150: but the brains of modern hagfishes
column16155: and mammals show a gradient of size and complexity that roughly follows the evolutionary sequence. All of these brains contain the same set of basic anatomical components
column16156: but many are rudimentary in the hagfish
column16157: whereas in mammals the foremost part (the telencephalon) is greatly elaborated and expanded.Brains are most commonly compared in terms of their size. The relationship between brain size
column16158: body size and other variables has been studied across a wide range of vertebrate species. As a rule
column16159: brain size increases with body size
column16160: but not in a simple linear proportion. In general
column16161: smaller animals tend to have larger brains
column16162: measured as a fraction of body size. For mammals
column16163: the relationship between brain volume and body mass essentially follows a power law with an exponent of about 0.75. This formula describes the central tendency
column16164: but every family of mammals departs from it to some degree
column16165: in a way that reflects in part the complexity of their behavior. For example
column16166: primates have brains 5 to 10 times larger than the formula predicts. Predators tend to have larger brains than their prey
column16167: relative to body size.All vertebrate brains share a common underlying form
column16168: which appears most clearly during early stages of embryonic development. In its earliest form
column16169: the brain appears as three swellings at the front end of the neural tube; these swellings eventually become the forebrain
column16174: respectively). At the earliest stages of brain development
column16175: the three areas are roughly equal in size. In many classes of vertebrates
column16177: the three parts remain similar in size in the adult
column16178: but in mammals the forebrain becomes much larger than the other parts
column16179: and the midbrain becomes very small.The brains of vertebrates are made of very soft tissue. Living brain tissue is pinkish on the outside and mostly white on the inside
column16180: with subtle variations in color. Vertebrate brains are surrounded by a system of connective tissue membranes called meninges that separate the skull from the brain. Blood vessels enter the central nervous system through holes in the meningeal layers. The cells in the blood vessel walls are joined tightly to one another
column16182: which blocks the passage of many toxins and pathogens (though at the same time blocking antibodies and some drugs
column16183: thereby presenting special challenges in treatment of diseases of the brain).Neuroanatomists usually divide the vertebrate brain into six main regions: the telencephalon (cerebral hemispheres)
column16188: and medulla oblongata. Each of these areas has a complex internal structure. Some parts
column16189: such as the cerebral cortex and the cerebellar cortex
column16190: consist of layers that are folded or convoluted to fit within the available space. Other parts
column16191: such as the thalamus and hypothalamus
column16192: consist of clusters of many small nuclei. Thousands of distinguishable areas can be identified within the vertebrate brain based on fine distinctions of neural structure
column16194: and connectivity.Although the same basic components are present in all vertebrate brains
column16195: some branches of vertebrate evolution have led to substantial distortions of brain geometry
column16196: especially in the forebrain area. The brain of a shark shows the basic components in a straightforward way
column16197: but in teleost fishes (the great majority of existing fish species)
column16199: like a sock turned inside out. In birds
column16200: there are also major changes in forebrain structure. These distortions can make it difficult to match brain components from one species with those of another species.Here is a list of some of the most important vertebrate brain components
column16201: along with a brief description of their functions as currently understood:The medulla
column16203: contains many small nuclei involved in a wide variety of sensory and involuntary motor functions such as vomiting
column16204: heart rate and digestive processes.The pons lies in the brainstem directly above the medulla. Among other things
column16205: it contains nuclei that control often voluntary but simple acts such as sleep
column16212: and posture.The hypothalamus is a small region at the base of the forebrain
column16213: whose complexity and importance belies its size. It is composed of numerous small nuclei
column16214: each with distinct connections and neurochemistry. The hypothalamus is engaged in additional involuntary or partially voluntary acts such as sleep and wake cycles
column16216: and the release of some hormones.The thalamus is a collection of nuclei with diverse functions: some are involved in relaying information to and from the cerebral hemispheres
column16217: while others are involved in motivation. The subthalamic area (zona incerta) seems to contain action-generating systems for several types of \"consummatory\" behaviors such as eating
column16220: and copulation.The cerebellum modulates the outputs of other brain systems
column16222: to make them certain and precise. Removal of the cerebellum does not prevent an animal from doing anything in particular
column16223: but it makes actions hesitant and clumsy. This precision is not built-in but learned by trial and error. The muscle coordination learned while riding a bicycle is an example of a type of neural plasticity that may take place largely within the cerebellum. 10% of the brain's total volume consists of the cerebellum and 50% of all neurons are held within its structure.The optic tectum allows actions to be directed toward points in space
column16224: most commonly in response to visual input. In mammals
column16225: it is usually referred to as the superior colliculus
column16226: and its best-studied function is to direct eye movements. It also directs reaching movements and other object-directed actions. It receives strong visual inputs
column16227: but also inputs from other senses that are useful in directing actions
column16228: such as auditory input in owls and input from the thermosensitive pit organs in snakes. In some primitive fishes
column16230: this region is the largest part of the brain. The superior colliculus is part of the midbrain.The pallium is a layer of grey matter that lies on the surface of the forebrain and is the most complex and most recent evolutionary development of the brain as an organ. In reptiles and mammals
column16231: it is called the cerebral cortex. Multiple functions involve the pallium
column16232: including smell and spatial memory. In mammals
column16233: where it becomes so large as to dominate the brain
column16234: it takes over functions from many other brain areas. In many mammals
column16235: the cerebral cortex consists of folded bulges called gyri that create deep furrows or fissures called sulci. The folds increase the surface area of the cortex and therefore increase the amount of gray matter and the amount of information that can be stored and processed.The hippocampus
column16237: is found only in mammals. However
column16240: has counterparts in all vertebrates. There is evidence that this part of the brain is involved in complex events such as spatial memory and navigation in fishes
column16243: and mammals.The basal ganglia are a group of interconnected structures in the forebrain. The primary function of the basal ganglia appears to be action selection: they send inhibitory signals to all parts of the brain that can generate motor behaviors
column16244: and in the right circumstances can release the inhibition
column16245: so that the action-generating systems are able to execute their actions. Reward and punishment exert their most important neural effects by altering connections within the basal ganglia.The olfactory bulb is a special structure that processes olfactory sensory signals and sends its output to the olfactory part of the pallium. It is a major brain component in many vertebrates
column16246: but is greatly reduced in humans and other primates (whose senses are dominated by information acquired by sight rather than smell).ReptilesBirdsMammalsThe most obvious difference between the brains of mammals and other vertebrates is in terms of size. On average
column16247: a mammal has a brain roughly twice as large as that of a bird of the same body size
column16248: and ten times as large as that of a reptile of the same body size.Size
column16250: is not the only difference: there are also substantial differences in shape. The hindbrain and midbrain of mammals are generally similar to those of other vertebrates
column16251: but dramatic differences appear in the forebrain
column16252: which is greatly enlarged and also altered in structure. The cerebral cortex is the part of the brain that most strongly distinguishes mammals. In non-mammalian vertebrates
column16253: the surface of the cerebrum is lined with a comparatively simple three-layered structure called the pallium. In mammals
column16254: the pallium evolves into a complex six-layered structure called neocortex or isocortex. Several areas at the edge of the neocortex
column16256: are also much more extensively developed in mammals than in other vertebrates.The elaboration of the cerebral cortex carries with it changes to other brain areas. The superior colliculus
column16257: which plays a major role in visual control of behavior in most vertebrates
column16258: shrinks to a small size in mammals
column16259: and many of its functions are taken over by visual areas of the cerebral cortex. The cerebellum of mammals contains a large portion (the neocerebellum) dedicated to supporting the cerebral cortex
column16260: which has no counterpart in other vertebrates.PrimatesThe brains of humans and other primates contain the same structures as the brains of other mammals
column16261: but are generally larger in proportion to body size. The encephalization quotient (EQ) is used to compare brain sizes across species. It takes into account the nonlinearity of the brain-to-body relationship. Humans have an average EQ in the 7-to-8 range
column16262: while most other primates have an EQ in the 2-to-3 range. Dolphins have values higher than those of primates other than humans
column16263: but nearly all other mammals have EQ values that are substantially lower.Most of the enlargement of the primate brain comes from a massive expansion of the cerebral cortex
column16264: especially the prefrontal cortex and the parts of the cortex involved in vision. The visual processing network of primates includes at least 30 distinguishable brain areas
column16265: with a complex web of interconnections. It has been estimated that visual processing areas occupy more than half of the total surface of the primate neocortex. The prefrontal cortex carries out functions that include planning
column16269: and executive control. It takes up a much larger proportion of the brain for primates than for other species
column16270: and an especially large fraction of the human brain.DevelopmentThe brain develops in an intricately orchestrated sequence of stages. It changes in shape from a simple swelling at the front of the nerve cord in the earliest embryonic stages
column16271: to a complex array of areas and connections. Neurons are created in special zones that contain stem cells
column16272: and then migrate through the tissue to reach their ultimate locations. Once neurons have positioned themselves
column16273: their axons sprout and navigate through the brain
column16274: branching and extending as they go
column16275: until the tips reach their targets and form synaptic connections. In a number of parts of the nervous system
column16276: neurons and synapses are produced in excessive numbers during the early stages
column16277: and then the unneeded ones are pruned away.For vertebrates
column16278: the early stages of neural development are similar across all species. As the embryo transforms from a round blob of cells into a wormlike structure
column16279: a narrow strip of ectoderm running along the midline of the back is induced to become the neural plate
column16280: the precursor of the nervous system. The neural plate folds inward to form the neural groove
column16281: and then the lips that line the groove merge to enclose the neural tube
column16282: a hollow cord of cells with a fluid-filled ventricle at the center. At the front end
column16283: the ventricles and cord swell to form three vesicles that are the precursors of the prosencephalon (forebrain)
column16285: and rhombencephalon (hindbrain). At the next stage
column16286: the forebrain splits into two vesicles called the telencephalon (which will contain the cerebral cortex
column16288: and related structures) and the diencephalon (which will contain the thalamus and hypothalamus). At about the same time
column16289: the hindbrain splits into the metencephalon (which will contain the cerebellum and pons) and the myelencephalon (which will contain the medulla oblongata). Each of these areas contains proliferative zones where neurons and glial cells are generated; the resulting cells then migrate
column16291: to their final positions.Once a neuron is in place
column16292: it extends dendrites and an axon into the area around it. Axons
column16293: because they commonly extend a great distance from the cell body and need to reach specific targets
column16294: grow in a particularly complex way. The tip of a growing axon consists of a blob of protoplasm called a growth cone
column16295: studded with chemical receptors. These receptors sense the local environment
column16296: causing the growth cone to be attracted or repelled by various cellular elements
column16297: and thus to be pulled in a particular direction at each point along its path. The result of this pathfinding process is that the growth cone navigates through the brain until it reaches its destination area
column16298: where other chemical cues cause it to begin generating synapses. Considering the entire brain
column16299: thousands of genes create products that influence axonal pathfinding.The synaptic network that finally emerges is only partly determined by genes
column16300: though. In many parts of the brain
column16302: and then are \"pruned\" by mechanisms that depend on neural activity. In the projection from the eye to the midbrain
column16304: the structure in the adult contains a very precise mapping
column16305: connecting each point on the surface of the retina to a corresponding point in a midbrain layer. In the first stages of development
column16306: each axon from the retina is guided to the right general vicinity in the midbrain by chemical cues
column16307: but then branches very profusely and makes initial contact with a wide swath of midbrain neurons. The retina
column16309: contains special mechanisms that cause it to generate waves of activity that originate spontaneously at a random point and then propagate slowly across the retinal layer. These waves are useful because they cause neighboring neurons to be active at the same time; that is
column16310: they produce a neural activity pattern that contains information about the spatial arrangement of the neurons. This information is exploited in the midbrain by a mechanism that causes synapses to weaken
column16312: if activity in an axon is not followed by activity of the target cell. The result of this sophisticated process is a gradual tuning and tightening of the map
column16313: leaving it finally in its precise adult form.Similar things happen in other brain areas: an initial synaptic matrix is generated as a result of genetically determined chemical guidance
column16314: but then gradually refined by activity-dependent mechanisms
column16316: partly by external sensory inputs. In some cases
column16318: activity patterns depend on mechanisms that operate only in the developing brain
column16319: and apparently exist solely to guide development.In humans and many other mammals
column16320: new neurons are created mainly before birth
column16321: and the infant brain contains substantially more neurons than the adult brain. There are
column16323: a few areas where new neurons continue to be generated throughout life. The two areas for which adult neurogenesis is well established are the olfactory bulb
column16324: which is involved in the sense of smell
column16325: and the dentate gyrus of the hippocampus
column16326: where there is evidence that the new neurons play a role in storing newly acquired memories. With these exceptions
column16328: the set of neurons that is present in early childhood is the set that is present for life. Glial cells are different: as with most types of cells in the body
column16329: they are generated throughout the lifespan.There has long been debate about whether the qualities of mind
column16331: and intelligence can be attributed to heredity or to upbringingthis is the nature and nurture controversy. Although many details remain to be settled
column16332: neuroscience research has clearly shown that both factors are important. Genes determine the general form of the brain
column16333: and genes determine how the brain reacts to experience. Experience
column16335: is required to refine the matrix of synaptic connections
column16336: which in its developed form contains far more information than the genome does. In some respects
column16337: all that matters is the presence or absence of experience during critical periods of development. In other respects
column16338: the quantity and quality of experience are important; for example
column16339: there is substantial evidence that animals raised in enriched environments have thicker cerebral cortices
column16340: indicating a higher density of synaptic connections
column16341: than animals whose levels of stimulation are restricted.PhysiologyThe functions of the brain depend on the ability of neurons to transmit electrochemical signals to other cells
column16342: and their ability to respond appropriately to electrochemical signals received from other cells. The electrical properties of neurons are controlled by a wide variety of biochemical and metabolic processes
column16343: most notably the interactions between neurotransmitters and receptors that take place at synapses.Neurotransmitters and receptorsNeurotransmitters are chemicals that are released at synapses when the local membrane is depolarised and Ca2+ enters into the cell
column16344: typically when an action potential arrives at the synapse  neurotransmitters attach themselves to receptor molecules on the membrane of the synapse's target cell (or cells)
column16345: and thereby alter the electrical or chemical properties of the receptor molecules.With few exceptions
column16346: each neuron in the brain releases the same chemical neurotransmitter
column16348: at all the synaptic connections it makes with other neurons; this rule is known as Dale's principle. Thus
column16349: a neuron can be characterized by the neurotransmitters that it releases. The great majority of psychoactive drugs exert their effects by altering specific neurotransmitter systems. This applies to drugs such as cannabinoids
column16356: and many others.The two neurotransmitters that are most widely found in the vertebrate brain are glutamate
column16357: which almost always exerts excitatory effects on target neurons
column16359: which is almost always inhibitory. Neurons using these transmitters can be found in nearly every part of the brain. Because of their ubiquity
column16360: drugs that act on glutamate or GABA tend to have broad and powerful effects. Some general anesthetics act by reducing the effects of glutamate; most tranquilizers exert their sedative effects by enhancing the effects of GABA.There are dozens of other chemical neurotransmitters that are used in more limited areas of the brain
column16361: often areas dedicated to a particular function. Serotonin
column16362: for examplethe primary target of many antidepressant drugs and many dietary aidscomes exclusively from a small brainstem area called the raphe nuclei. Norepinephrine
column16364: comes exclusively from a nearby small area called the locus coeruleus. Other neurotransmitters such as acetylcholine and dopamine have multiple sources in the brain but are not as ubiquitously distributed as glutamate and GABA.Electrical activityAs a side effect of the electrochemical processes used by neurons for signaling
column16365: brain tissue generates electric fields when it is active. When large numbers of neurons show synchronized activity
column16366: the electric fields that they generate can be large enough to detect outside the skull
column16367: using electroencephalography (EEG) or magnetoencephalography (MEG). EEG recordings
column16368: along with recordings made from electrodes implanted inside the brains of animals such as rats
column16369: show that the brain of a living animal is constantly active
column16370: even during sleep. Each part of the brain shows a mixture of rhythmic and nonrhythmic activity
column16371: which may vary according to behavioral state. In mammals
column16372: the cerebral cortex tends to show large slow delta waves during sleep
column16373: faster alpha waves when the animal is awake but inattentive
column16374: and chaotic-looking irregular activity when the animal is actively engaged in a task
column16375: called beta and gamma waves. During an epileptic seizure
column16376: the brain's inhibitory control mechanisms fail to function and electrical activity rises to pathological levels
column16377: producing EEG traces that show large wave and spike patterns not seen in a healthy brain. Relating these population-level patterns to the computational functions of individual neurons is a major focus of current research in neurophysiology.MetabolismAll vertebrates have a bloodbrain barrier that allows metabolism inside the brain to operate differently from metabolism in other parts of the body. The neurovascular unit regulates cerebral blood flow so that activated neurons can be supplied with energy. Glial cells play a major role in brain metabolism by controlling the chemical composition of the fluid that surrounds neurons
column16378: including levels of ions and nutrients.Brain tissue consumes a large amount of energy in proportion to its volume
column16379: so large brains place severe metabolic demands on animals. The need to limit body weight in order
column16382: has apparently led to selection for a reduction of brain size in some species
column16383: such as bats. Most of the brain's energy consumption goes into sustaining the electric charge (membrane potential) of neurons. Most vertebrate species devote between 2% and 8% of basal metabolism to the brain. In primates
column16385: the percentage is much higherin humans it rises to 2025%. The energy consumption of the brain does not vary greatly over time
column16386: but active regions of the cerebral cortex consume somewhat more energy than inactive regions; this forms the basis for the functional brain imaging methods of PET
column16388: and NIRS. The brain typically gets most of its energy from oxygen-dependent metabolism of glucose (i.e.
column16390: but ketones provide a major alternative source
column16391: together with contributions from medium chain fatty acids (caprylic and heptanoic acids)
column16394: and possibly amino acids.FunctionInformation from the sense organs is collected in the brain. There it is used to determine what actions the organism is to take. The brain processes the raw data to extract information about the structure of the environment. Next it combines the processed information with information about the current needs of the animal and with memory of past circumstances. Finally
column16395: on the basis of the results
column16396: it generates motor response patterns. These signal-processing tasks require intricate interplay between a variety of functional subsystems.The function of the brain is to provide coherent control over the actions of an animal. A centralized brain allows groups of muscles to be co-activated in complex patterns; it also allows stimuli impinging on one part of the body to evoke responses in other parts
column16397: and it can prevent different parts of the body from acting at cross-purposes to each other.PerceptionThe human brain is provided with information about light
column16399: the chemical composition of the atmosphere
column16401: the position of the body in space (proprioception)
column16402: the chemical composition of the bloodstream
column16403: and more. In other animals additional senses are present
column16404: such as the infrared heat-sense of snakes
column16405: the magnetic field sense of some birds
column16406: or the electric field sense mainly seen in aquatic animals.Each sensory system begins with specialized receptor cells
column16407: such as photoreceptor cells in the retina of the eye
column16408: or vibration-sensitive hair cells in the cochlea of the ear. The axons of sensory receptor cells travel into the spinal cord or brain
column16409: where they transmit their signals to a first-order sensory nucleus dedicated to one specific sensory modality. This primary sensory nucleus sends information to higher-order sensory areas that are dedicated to the same modality. Eventually
column16410: via a way-station in the thalamus

column17042: using visual stimuli modulated at certain frequencies. SSVEP's stimuli are often formed from alternating checkerboard patterns and at times simply use flashing images. SSVEP has proved to be successful within many BCI systems. This is due to several factors

column17048: which can often last more than an hour which may not be an ideal gameplay.Another type of VEP used with applications is the P300 potential. The P300 event-related potential is a positive peak in the EEG that occurs at roughly 300 ms after the appearance of a target stimulus (a stimulus for which the user is waiting or seeking) or oddball stimuli. The P300 amplitude decreases as the target stimuli and the ignored stimuli grow more similar.The P300 is thought to be related to a higher level attention process or an orienting response using P300 as a control scheme has the advantage of the participant only having to attend limited training sessions. The first application to use the P300 model was the P300 matrix. Within this system

column17136: )Disorders of consciousness (DOC)Some people have a disorder of consciousness (DOC). This state is defined to include people in a coma and those in a vegetative state (VS) or minimally conscious state (MCS). New BCI research seeks to help people with DOC in different ways. A key initial goal is to identify patients who can perform basic cognitive tasks
column17137: which would of course lead to a change in their diagnosis. That is
column17138: some people who are diagnosed with DOC may in fact be able to process information and make important life decisions (such as whether to seek therapy
column17140: and their views on end-of-life decisions regarding them). Some who are diagnosed with DOC die as a result of end-of-life decisions
column17141: which may be made by family members who sincerely feel this is in the patient's best interests. Given the new prospect of allowing these patients to provide their views on this decision
column17142: there would seem to be a strong ethical pressure to develop this research direction to guarantee that DOC patients are given an opportunity to decide whether they want to live.These and other articles describe new challenges and solutions to use BCI technology to help persons with DOC. One major challenge is that these patients cannot use BCIs based on vision. Hence
column17143: new tools rely on auditory and/or vibrotactile stimuli. Patients may wear headphones and/or vibrotactile stimulators placed on the wrists
column17146: and/or other locations. Another challenge is that patients may fade in and out of consciousness and can only communicate at certain times. This may indeed be a cause of mistaken diagnosis. Some patients may only be able to respond to physicians' requests for a few hours per day (which might not be predictable ahead of time) and thus may have been unresponsive during diagnosis. Therefore
column17147: new methods rely on tools that are easy to use in field settings
column17149: so family members and other people without any medical or technical background can still use them. This reduces the cost

column17159: and otherwise empower them to make major life decisions and communicate.Motor recoveryPeople may lose some of their ability to move due to many causes

Research in recent years has demonstrated the utility of EEG-based BCI systems in aiding motor recovery and neurorehabilitation in patients who have had a stroke. Several groups have explored systems and methods for motor recovery that include BCIs. In this approach
column17161: a BCI measures motor activity while the patient imagines or attempts movements as directed by a therapist. The BCI may provide two benefits: (1) if the BCI indicates that a patient is not imagining a movement correctly (non-compliance)

column17170: 000 people undergo brain mapping during neurosurgery. This procedure is often required for people with tumors or epilepsy that do not respond to medication. During this procedure
column17171: electrodes are placed on the brain to precisely identify the locations of structures and functional areas. Patients may be awake during neurosurgery and asked to perform certain tasks
column17172: such as moving fingers or repeating words. This is necessary so that surgeons can remove only the desired tissue while sparing other regions
column17173: such as critical movement or language regions. Removing too much brain tissue can cause permanent damage
column17174: while removing too little tissue can leave the underlying condition untreated and require additional neurosurgery. Thus
column17175: there is a strong need to improve both methods and systems to map the brain as effectively as possible.In several recent publications

Using only the centroid to redistribute the data has problems when clusters lack uniform sizes and shapes.CURE clustering algorithmTo avoid the problems with non-uniform sized or shaped clusters
column17204: CURE employs a hierarchical clustering algorithm that adopts a middle ground between the centroid based and all point extremes. In CURE
column17205: a constant number c of well scattered points of a cluster are chosen and they are shrunk towards the centroid of the cluster by a fraction . The scattered points after shrinking are used as representatives of the cluster. The clusters with the closest pair of representatives are the clusters that are merged at each step of CURE's hierarchical clustering algorithm. This enables CURE to correctly identify the clusters and makes it less sensitive to outliers.Running time is O(n2 log n)
column17207: and space complexity is O(n).The algorithm cannot be directly applied to large databases because of the high runtime complexity. Enhancements address this requirement.Random sampling :random sampling supports large data sets. Generally the random sample fits in main memory. The random sampling involves a trade off between accuracy and efficiency.Partitioning : The basic idea is to partition the sample space into p partitions. Each partition contains n/p elements. The first pass partially clusters each partition until the final number of clusters reduces to n/pq for some constant q  1. A second clustering pass on n/q partially clusters partitions. For the second pass only the representative points are stored since the merge procedure only requires representative points of previous clusters before computing the representative points for the merged cluster. Partitioning the input reduces the execution times.Labeling data on disk : Given only representative points for k clusters
